         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 4/6/70 ¶  ¶ The young fern tree, sent by you, dear Mr Boyle, interests me much. It is quite different not only from the Dicksonia Antarctica &amp; Alsophila australis, but also from...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">70.06.04a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To David Boyle</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Private hands.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Published in Pretlove (2012), p. 74.</p>
               </note>Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">4/6/70</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The young fern tree, sent by you, dear Mr Boyle, interests me much. It is quite different not only from the <name key="Dicksonia%20Antarctica%20">Dicksonia Antarctica </name>&amp; <name key="Alsophila%20australis">Alsophila australis</name>, but also from <name key="Cyathea%20medullaris">Cyathea medullaris</name>, found at Cape Otway. You may be right, that it is my <name key="Alsophila%20Leichhardtiana">Alsophila Leichhardtiana</name>, but your plant has broader scales to the stakes of the fronds and the rachis is less prickly rough. These differences might however be only those of youth. The <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">fruit</hi>
               </seg> must show it, which is not developed on your plant. I see also some difference in the denticulations of the lobes of the fronds but these also may arise only from the young age. As soon as the exact species will have been ascertained I will make <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">your</hi>
               </seg> discovery known</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">your regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Alsophila%20australis">Alsophila australis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Alsophila%20Leichhardtiana">Alsophila Leichhardtiana</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Cyathea%20medullaris">Cyathea medullaris</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dicksonia%20Antarctica%20">Dicksonia Antarctica </name>
            </p>
         </div>
